dream_report: I was jumping from place to place and scenario to scenario, but they all made me feel stressed and anxious. By the way, I was lucid dreaming and knew that I was dreaming the entire time. Now back to the dream. I was at first "woken" from my sleep even though I was still dreaming and was running late to work and had overslept and missed my alarm. I get dressed as quickly as I could and felt like I almost teleported to work. While at work I kept feeling this uneasiness as if I was missing something. Work continued until it hit me that I had an assignment due from my chemistry class and for some reason had an exam. The setting then abruptly shifts and I am now in the exam room of gray little taking an exam over equilibrium constants, acids and bases, etc. As I'm looking at these questions, there's information missing as if they're almost a blurry film over them. I begin to panic as I don't understand what I'm looking at and can't answer the questions. There's then this nagging feeling that I need to wake up, for context I have work in morning at 7am and I feel like I'm oversleeping, so I all of sudden jolt awake and see that it's 4:30am and that I haven't overslept. I then fall back asleep and didn't have any vivid dream I could remember.
dream_type_5_TEXT: It was like a mix of second and fourth answers where I was stressed and anxious, but I did jolt awake like described in the fourth answer.
dream_behavior_fr: After experiencing the dream I began to crack down on studying for not only chemistry, but all of my classes as a way to possibly stop that dream from reoccurring. Also, it has reinforced my nightly habit of checking and setting my alarms for the next day.
other_trauma_fr: It made it difficult for me to not only fall asleep but also stay asleep as I'd jolt awake from my sleep at least once each time. But after about a week my sleep would slowly return to  how it was before the event.

There was a person in charge assigning everyone directions and coaching everyone. Everyone kept working. I sat there frozen because I felt paralyzed from my anxiety. I tried to go along with it and act like I was typing on my computer like everyone else. I was still confused at this point, but once everyone started to walk out of the room I left with the crowd and realized what happened. I walked into a room where there was a "study group" and everyone who was in the room was receiving extra credit for a class. Then the group walked outside into a lobby. A woman was handing out snacks and offered me one first. I accepted it and thanked her, but was still confused. It was gelatin based food that she said had several health benefits. She gave me two servings. After I finished it, I noticed that no one else ate it. Then, another person in charge of the group asked if there was enough  for everyone. I overheard her say this and was more confused. Someone answered her and said yes, but just one for everyone. People kept staring at me and one person who I recognized laughed at me. Then I woke up.

dream_report:
I find myself standing on the edge of a vast, tranquil lake. The surface of the water is perfectly still, reflecting the sky above like a mirror. The air is warm, and the scent of flowers and fresh grass fills my lungs with every breath. The sun is low on the horizon, casting a soft, golden glow over everything, turning the water into liquid light. I feel a deep sense of peace here, like time itself has slowed down.

I take a step forward, my feet sinking slightly into the soft earth beneath me. The sound of the water lapping gently at the shore fills the air, and I feel drawn to it, almost as if the lake is calling me. Without thinking, I slip off my shoes and step into the water. It's cool and refreshing, the sensation sending a shiver up my spine as I wade deeper, the water rippling around my legs.

As I walk further, I notice something unusuala large, smooth stone rising out of the lake, like a natural platform. Its perfectly round, covered in moss and small flowers. Intrigued, I make my way toward it, the water barely reaching my knees now. The stone feels warm under my feet as I step onto it, and I sit down, gazing out across the lake. The stillness is comforting, the world around me soft and full of possibility.

Suddenly, a soft light appears on the horizon, growing brighter as it comes closer. Its not like the sun, but something elseshimmering and ethereal, like a star falling from the sky. It hovers just above the water, casting gentle beams of light across the surface. I watch in awe, feeling no fear, only wonder. The light moves toward me, and as it does, the water beneath it begins to glow in response.

Then, something shiftsslowly, almost imperceptiblyand I realize Im no longer alone. A figure materializes from the light, their shape ethereal, but undeniably present. They are tall, dressed in flowing robes of soft white and gold, their face glowing but unformed, as if its not quite meant to be seen. But I can feel their presence deeply, like theyve always been a part of me.

The figure steps closer, and as they do, a sense of understanding washes over me. Its not through words, but through a knowing. They reach out, their hand hovering just in front of mine. I hesitate for only a moment before I take it. The moment my fingers brush theirs, I feel a surge of warmtha warmth that spreads through me, filling me with peace and clarity. The figures presence is grounding, yet freeing, and I realize that they are both guiding me and reminding me of something Ive always known.

Without speaking, they gesture toward the glowing water, and I look down. The surface is now a canvas, a swirling tapestry of colors and patternsimages of moments from my past, my present, and even glimpses of what might be. The water shows me the path Ive walked, and the path that lies ahead, shifting and changing with every glance.

The figure nods once, as if to say, "Youre on the right path. Trust what you see, trust what you feel." Then, as quietly as they came, the figure begins to fade back into the light, leaving me with the lake, the warmth, and a newfound sense of direction.

I stay on the stone, my fingers still tingling from the touch, and watch as the light dissolves into the sky. The lake, now calm and clear again, reflects the stars as night falls. I feel a deep sense of peace, as if Ive just been given a gift I didnt know I needed. I stand slowly, taking one last look at the serene water before I turn and walk back along the shore, feeling lighter, like something inside me has shifted into place.

The building is tall and silver. She has a short light brown bob and blue eyes, and waves with her left hand. She is wearing a purple and orange striped turtleneck. Me and my ex boyfriend turn back to each other, and communicate that the conversation was nice, and we are both glad we could finally mature enough to have the conversation at all.
